supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, 1-278. domine obsecro complaceat tibi

p.note: Top of page, in ink by a conteporary hand over 5 lines, a table of contents: In isto volumine continetur tractatus infrascripti Primo Sermones Beatis Bernhardi de toto anno Item acta consilii Basilensis Item tractatus de arta moriendi Item tractatus de miseria humane condicionis; bottom right corner: National Library book label with the current signum.

Top of page, in ink in the hand of Hyltén-Cavallius: 1734 års Katal. Theol. in folio, no 23.; centre page, in the same hand: a table of contents with the folio numbers added in pencil in a different hand, I Sermones beati Bernhardi Abbatis de adventu domini et de toto anno fol. 1-20 II Acta Sacri Basilensis concilii fol. 201-253 III Tractatus de arte moriendi fol. 236-263 IV Liber Lotharii dyaconi Cardinalis qui postea Innocentius papa IIIus appelatus est De miseria humanae condicionis fol. 264-277, and an addition in pencil below, V predikoturer för var månad 1435, 1436, och 1437.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 5 double raised bands and endbands. Hooked clasps with straps of green facbric. Decorated centre and corner bosses. Spine, in ink on a paper label: In hoc volumine contin. i Sermones beati Bernhardi 2 Acta concilii Basil. 3 Tract. de arte moriendi 4 ---- humanae miseria condicionis ; in ink on a paper label: No 23 1. Sermones Bernhardi 2. Acta Concilii Basil. etc.; stamped in gold: the current signum, A 206; in ink on a paper label: Bernhardi sermones etc 23; in ink on a paper label, on top of the remnants of another paper label: e. 30. 3. 10..
binding.decoNote: Blind tooled panels with lozenge patterns inside on and .
binding.condition: The leather is worn and, on , cracked along the spine. One of the fabric straps has been replaced with modern leather.

history.provenance: The manuscript has been at the National Library since at least the 18th century; it is listed in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125 e) as no 23. and as e. 30. 3. 10. in Hammarskölds catalogue of the 19th century. The signum 96 on the spine has not been identified.
